<section xml:id="sec-p5js-demo">
  <title>Your First Sketch: Drawing a Line</title>
  <p>
    Every p5.js sketch is built around two functions.
    <c>setup()</c> runs exactly once when the sketch starts — use it to create the canvas.
    <c>draw()</c> runs repeatedly, once per frame — use it to draw things.
  </p>
  <p>
    The sketch below calls <c>line(x1, y1, x2, y2)</c> to draw a straight line.
    The four arguments are the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> coordinates of the start point,
    followed by the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> coordinates of the end point.
    Notice that <m>(0, 0)</m> is the <em>top-left</em> corner of the canvas.
  </p>
  <p>
    Press <em>Run</em> to see it in action, then try changing the numbers and running again.
  </p>

  <program xml:id="p5js-line-example" interactive="activecode" language="html">

    <preamble visible="no">
      <![CDATA[<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <script src="external/p5.min.js"></script>
</head>
<body>]]>
    </preamble>

    <code>
<![CDATA[<script>

  function setup() {
    createCanvas(400, 300);
  }

  function draw() {
    background(220);
    line(50, 50, 350, 250);
  }
  
</script>]]>
    </code>

  </program>
  <p>next section of material asdf adsf afsd fsdfewgfewa ewg aw gag sgga grgra gr garwgegw</p>
</section>
